│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs during instsimplify when folding a load from a constant      │
│ initializer. Specifically, the reproducer loads an i8 from a GEP that points  │
│ to byte offset 6 of a global struct { i40, i8 } with initializer { i40 0, i8  │
│ 1 }. The instsimplify pass attempts to constant-fold the load, which leads    │
│ into ConstantFolding.cpp's ReadDataFromGlobal(). The assertion in             │
│ APInt::extractBits indicates an attempt to extract bits beyond the bitwidth   │
│ of the APInt (40 bits).                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The backtrace shows the first transformation occurs inside                    │
│ ReadDataFromGlobal(), called via FoldReinterpretLoadFromConst ->              │
│ ConstantFoldLoadFromConstPtr -> simplifyLoadInst. The debug state at frame 2  │
│ shows:                                                                        │
│ - C is a ConstantInt of type i40 with value 0.                                │
│ - ByteOffset = 6                                                              │
│ - IntBytes = 5 (40 bits / 8)                                                  │
│ - DataLayout is little-endian.                                                │
│ - BytesLeft = 1.                                                              │
│ The code path is in the ConstantInt branch of ReadDataFromGlobal.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In the ConstantInt branch, the loop is:                                       │
│   for (unsigned i = 0; i != BytesLeft && ByteOffset != IntBytes; ++i) {       │
│     unsigned n = ByteOffset;                                                  │
│     if (!DL.isLittleEndian())                                                 │
│       n = IntBytes - n - 1;                                                   │
│     CurPtr[i] = Val.extractBits(8, n * 8).getZExtValue();                     │
│     ++ByteOffset;                                                             │
│   }                                                                           │
│ Here, the guard uses 'ByteOffset != IntBytes', which permits ByteOffset >     │
│ IntBytes to enter the loop. In the reproducer, ByteOffset is 6 while IntBytes │
│ is 5, so the condition is true and the loop executes with n = 6, leading to   │
│ extractBits(8, 48) on a 40-bit APInt, triggering the assertion. The correct   │
│ semantics are to read only while ByteOffset < IntBytes. Any offset beyond the │
│ integer's allocated size should be treated as out-of-bounds for this element  │
│ (i.e., no bytes to read, and since CurPtr is zero-initialized, returning true │
│ is fine). This off-by-one/inequality bug causes the illegal extract.          │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Analysis/ConstantFolding.cpp, lines 446-452.                 │
│ Change the loop condition from 'ByteOffset != IntBytes' to 'ByteOffset <      │
│ IntBytes'. This ensures we only extract bits within the valid range of the    │
│ integer constant.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ Before:                                                                       │
│   for (unsigned i = 0; i != BytesLeft && ByteOffset != IntBytes; ++i) {       │
│     unsigned n = ByteOffset;                                                  │
│     if (!DL.isLittleEndian())                                                 │
│       n = IntBytes - n - 1;                                                   │
│     CurPtr[i] = Val.extractBits(8, n * 8).getZExtValue();                     │
│     ++ByteOffset;                                                             │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ After:                                                                        │
│   for (unsigned i = 0; i != BytesLeft && ByteOffset < IntBytes; ++i) {        │
│     unsigned n = ByteOffset;                                                  │
│     if (!DL.isLittleEndian())                                                 │
│       n = IntBytes - n - 1;                                                   │
│     CurPtr[i] = Val.extractBits(8, n * 8).getZExtValue();                     │
│     ++ByteOffset;                                                             │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This change prevents attempting to read bytes beyond the available bytes of   │
│ the integer constant, aligning with the earlier struct/vector handling that   │
│ already bounds reads by element size.                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The assertion arises from an incorrect loop guard in ReadDataFromGlobal for   │
│ ConstantInt, allowing out-of-bounds byte extraction when ByteOffset >         │
│ IntBytes. Changing the condition to ByteOffset < IntBytes fixes the crash by  │
│ restricting reads to the valid byte range. This will allow instsimplify's     │
│ constant folding to either read valid bytes or return zero for                │
│ padding/out-of-range cases, avoiding UB and assertions.                       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
